Package sprouts

Interface Tuple<T extends @Nullable Object>

Type Parameters:
T - The type of the items in the immutable tuple.
All Superinterfaces:
Iterable<T>
public interface Tuple<T extends @Nullable Object> extends Iterable<T>
An immutable collection of ordered items of the same type T (see type()), whose items can be iterated over and accessed through their indices.
This class can be thought of as an immutable array with an API designed for functional programming and robust handling of null values.

The name of this class was deliberately chosen because as a mathematical object, a tuple is not a place in memory where items are stored, but a sequence of raw pieces of information with value object semantics.
So two Tuple instances with the same items and the same order are considered equal, even if they are not the same object in memory.

Take a look at the living sprouts documentation for a large collection of examples demonstrating how to use the API of this class.

      static <T> Class<Tuple<T>> classTyped(Class<T> itemType)
      An alternative to Tuple.class which also includes the parameter type in the type signature of the returned tuple class. This is useful when you want to use tuple as items in collection types or in properties...
      Type Parameters:
      T - The type of item in the tuple class parameter signature.
      Parameters:
      itemType - The item type T in the returned Class<Tuple<T>>.
      Returns:

      Throws:
      NullPointerException - If the supplied type parameter is null.

    • collectorOf

      static <T> Collector<T,?,Tuple<T>> collectorOf(Class<T> type)
      Creates a Collector that can be used to collect a stream of items into a new tuple of non-nullable items. Here is an example demonstrating how this method may be used:
      
    var tuple = Stream.of("a", "b", "c")
                .map(String::toUpperCase)
                .collect(Tuple.collectorOf(String.class));
      This will create a new tuple of strings with the items "A", "B" and "C". If there are null values in the stream, an exception will be thrown. Use collectorOfNullable(Class) if you want to allow nulls.
      Type Parameters:
      T - The type of the items in the tuple.
      Parameters:
      type - The common type of the items in the tuple to be created.
      Returns:
      A collector that collects a stream of items into a new tuple of non-nullable items.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - If the supplied type is null.

    • collectorOfNullable

      static <T> Collector<T,?,Tuple<@Nullable T>> collectorOfNullable(Class<T> type)
      Use this to collect a stream of items into a new tuple of nullable items. Here is an example of how to use this method:
      
    var tuple = Stream.of("a", "b", "c")
                .map(String::toUpperCase)
                .collect(Tuple.collectorOfNullable(String.class));
      This will create a new tuple of strings with the items "A", "B" and "C". Null values in the stream will not lead to an exception when using this collector.
      Type Parameters:
      T - The type of the items in the tuple.
      Parameters:
      type - The type of the items in the tuple.
      Returns:
      A collector that collects a stream of items into a new tuple of nullable items.

    • removeIf

      default <V extends T> Tuple<T> removeIf(Class<V> type)
      Creates a new tuple containing only the items that are NOT instances of the specified type. This method filters out all items that are assignable to the given class, effectively retaining entries that do not match the specified type criteria.

      Example: 

      
 // Given a tuple with mixed types:
 var mixed = Tuple.of(Object.class, 1, "x", 2.5, "z", 3);

 // Remove all String instances
 Tuple<Object> withoutStrings = mixed.removeIf(String.class);
 // Result: [1, 2.5, 3]

      Null handling:
      • If this tuple allows null values (allowsNull() returns true), then null items will NOT be removed in the result since they cannot be instances of a class.
      • So the returned tuple will always have the same nullability policy as this instance!
      • If this tuple doesn't allow null values, null items cannot exist and so the result will also report false when invoking allowsNull()
      Type Parameters:
      V - The type to filter out, must be a subtype of the tuple's item type T.
      Parameters:
      type - The class type to filter out from the tuple. Items that are instances of this type (including subclasses) will be removed from the result.
      Returns:
      A new tuple containing only items that are not instances of the specified type (and possibly null entries if the original tuple also allowed nulls).
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if the provided type parameter is null.

    • retainIf

      default <V extends T> Tuple<V> retainIf(Class<V> type)
      Creates a new tuple containing only the items that are instances of the specified type. This method filters the tuple to retain all items that are assignable to the given class, effectively keeping entries that match the specified type criteria while removing all others.

      Example: 

      
 // Given a tuple with mixed types:
 var mixed = Tuple.of(Object.class, 1, "x", 2.5, "z", 3);

 // Keep only String instances
 Tuple<String> onlyStrings = mixed.retainIf(String.class);
 // Result: ["x", "z"]

      Type Safety: The returned tuple is explicitly typed with the specified class type V, allowing for type-safe operations on the filtered results without the need for explicit casting.

      Null handling:
      • Null items are always excluded from the result, regardless of this tuple's nullability policy, since null cannot be an instance of any class type.
      • The returned tuple will have non-nullable items (allowsNull() returns false), as it only contains valid instances of the specified type.
      • If this tuple contains null values but the specified type is not compatible with null, those null items will be filtered out in the result.

      Empty Result: If no items in this tuple match the specified type (including the case where all items are null), an empty tuple of type V will be returned.
      Type Parameters:
      V - The type to filter by, must be a subtype of the tuple's item type T.
      Parameters:
      type - The class type to filter by. Only items that are instances of this type (including subclasses) will be retained in the result.
      Returns:
      A new tuple containing only items that are instances of the specified type, with no null items, typed as Tuple<V>.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if the provided type parameter is null.

    • join

      default String join(String delimiter)
      Joins all items in this tuple into a single string using the specified delimiter. Each item is converted to a string using String.valueOf(Object).

      Example: 
      
 Tuple<String> tuple = Tuple.of(String.class, "a", "b", "c");
 String result = tuple.join(", "); // Returns "a, b, c"

 Tuple<Integer> numbers = Tuple.of(Integer.class, 1, 2, 3);
 String numbered = numbers.join("-"); // Returns "1-2-3"

      Null handling:
      • If this tuple contains null items and allows null values (allowsNull() returns true), the string "null" will be used for null items.
      • If the tuple is empty, an empty string is returned.
      Parameters:
      delimiter - the delimiter to place between each item in the resulting string
      Returns:
      a string containing all tuple items joined by the delimiter
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if the delimiter is null

    • equals

      boolean equals(Object o)
      Compares the specified object with this tuple for value equality. Returns true only if the specified object is also a tuple with the same size(), type(), and where every member of the specified tuple is contained in this tuple in the exact same order. This definition ensures that the equals method works properly across different implementations of the tuple interface.
      Overrides:
      equals in class Object
      Parameters:

      Returns:

    • hashCode

      int hashCode()
      Returns the hash code value for this tuple. The hash code of a tuple is sensitive to both what items exist in the tuple and in which order they are stored. This ensures that t1.equals(t2) implies that t1.hashCode()==t2.hashCode() for any two tuples t1 and t2, as required by the general contract of Object.hashCode().
      Overrides:
      hashCode in class Object
      Returns:
      The hash code value for this tuple as a 32-bit integer, based on the sum of the hash codes of all elements in this tuple.
